30|$|Mayr (2012) determines occupation-specific <b>immigration</b> <b>quotas</b> in a {{political}} economy framework with endogenous prices and compares them to the social optimum. It shows that positive quotas for specific occupations can be the political outcome, even when total welfare effects of immigration are negative. Two of the main findings are that the (unique) voting outcome on <b>immigration</b> <b>quotas</b> is i) positive if workers are immobile across occupations and ii) negative (positive) for occupations where the native labor supply is sufficiently large (small), if workers are mobile across occupations.|$|R
40|$|This paper {{develops}} a {{general equilibrium model}} of migration decisions to investi-gate the welfare and growth effect of immigration policy in host countries. A negative relationship is shown to exist between the domestic wage level {{and the percentage of}} educated workers among immigrants. Thus, the <b>immigration</b> <b>quota</b> should be set above a certain minimum level. to maximize national income. Extending the analysis to a dynamic setting, we highlight additional positive effects of the <b>immigration</b> <b>quota</b> on the average level of human capital and on economic growth...|$|R
